aces exist\", destructures the void, spirals on the recovered error, and re-emits `organize_material`. NOT a missing runtime boundary — THING should TRUST the tasklist envelope, not re-inspect the filesystem.\n85\t- **Direction (human, after R14):** L1 in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`. After `await tasklist('organize_material', …)`, THING TRUSTS the returned envelope (`r.ok` / `r.data`), composes ONE closing reply from it, and ENDS the turn. Make explicit: do NOT verify the build by inspecting the project (no `inspect()`/`listProjectDir` \"to confirm tables/spaces exist\") — the tasklist already built and registered everything and its envelope is the source of truth; re-inspecting is both wrong (`inspect` returns void → the `[Symbol.iterator]` throw) and spirals into re-running the whole workflow. General principle: after a workflow tasklist returns its envelope, an orchestrator reports from the envelope and stops — it does not re-derive success by reading the filesystem. This is NOT L3 — do not add a runtime single-execution guard. After this, re-check `built:false`: it is most likely the second (racing) automator run and should clear once the workflow runs once; if it persists with a single run, trace the automator finalize separately.\n86\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"625ee3e5-57b1-42a3-9cc2-762259deb6f8","uuid":"e88abdc5-0eb4-4b32-bc0f-dedd25607d1f","timestamp":"2026-07-16T03:30:29.525Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/attempts/06-tanzania.md","content":"# Attempt ledger — 06-tanzania\n\nCross-round memory for the judge. **Read this before attributing a failure**; **append one entry at\nthe end of every round.** One line per attempt. This is how a fresh-context round knows a rung is\nalready exhausted and it must CLIMB instead of re-trying the same rung.\n\nFormat per line:\n`R<round> · step <N> · <L0|L1|L2|L3> · <file#symbol> · verify=<PASS|FAIL|INT