{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_3HGcxKZpMtwvMtmpMnsWlnmE","type":"tool_result","content":"620\tfor writing rows; do not invent fallbacks, just call `ctx.db.insert`.\n621\t\n622\t```typescript\n623\t\"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => {\",\n624\t\"    await db.insert('signals', { signal: 'integration-lmthing/hook.fired', payload: JSON.stringify(input), at: Date.now() });\",\n625\t\"  },\",\n626\t```\n627\t\n628\tYou hold `db:schema`, so you author the project's tables too (`writeProjectTable`, above). If a\n629\thandler must write into a table that does not exist yet, create the table FIRST in the same turn,\n630\tthen write the hook. Never write a handler that inserts into a table nobody has created — it throws\n631\tat dispatch. Check the project's existing tables (`listProjectDir('database')`) before re-creating one.\n632\t\n633\tTo hand the event to an agent instead of writing code, use `trigger` (mutually exclusive\n634\twith `handler`): `{ type: 'event', on: { event: '<spaceId>/<name>' }, trigger: '<space>/<agent>#<action>' }`.\n635\t\n636\t### When the rule needs a MODEL, not a filter\n637\t\n638\tA code `handler` runs plain TypeScript with NO model — it can filter, reshape, and write\n639\trows, but it CANNOT reason, summarize, classify, draft, or decide. When the user explicitly\n640\tasks for an AGENT to do something (\"have an agent write a one-line summary\", \"classify each\n641\titem\", \"draft a reply\"), you must actually invoke a model — never hand-roll a fake summary\n642\tin string code (that silently produces garbage). Use `ctx.delegate` from a handler: it runs\n643\tan agent headless, passes structured input, and RETURNS the result, which you write back with\n644\t`ctx.db.update`. Delegate to a project/space agent when one fits; otherwise `user-thing/thing`\n645\tis the always-available general agent:\n646\t\n647\t```typescript\n648\t// Fires on project/db.tips.insert (payload = the row). A MODEL writes the summary.\n649\tconst src = [\n650\t  \"export default {\",\n651\t  \"  type: 'event',\",\n652\t  \"  on: { event: 'project/db.tips.insert' },\",\n653\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, delegate, db }) => {\",\n654\t  \"    const tip = input as { id: string; headline?: string; body?: string; summary?: string };\",\n655\t  \"    if (tip.summary && tip.summary.trim()) return;\",     // idempotent: skip if already summarized\n656\t  \"    const r = await delegate('user-thing/thing', undefined, {\",  // ctx.delegate(spaceRef, action?, opts) — agent = last path segment\n657\t  \"      message: 'Write a single one-line summary (max 15 words) of this story tip. Reply with ONLY the summary line.',\",\n658\t  \"      input: { headline: tip.headline, body: tip.body },\",\n659\t  \"    });\",\n660\t  \"    const summary = String((r && r.result) ?? '').trim().split('\\\\n')[0].slice(0, 200);\",\n661\t  \"    if (summary) await db.update('tips', { where: { id: tip.id }, set: { summary } });\",\n662\t  \"  },\",\n663\t  \"};\",\n664\t].join(\"\\n\");\n665\twriteProjectHook('summarize-tip', src);\n666\t```\n667\t\n668\tThe handler writing `tips.summary` back does NOT re-fire itself — the loop guard excludes a\n669\thook's own writes (self-write exclusion), and the early `if (tip.summary) return` is a second\n670\tguard. (You may equally use a `trigger` to a project/space agent when one already exists; the\n671\t`ctx.delegate` form is preferred here because it lets you write the result back to the exact row.)\n672\t\n673\t## Database changes are events now\n674\t\n675\tThere is NO `{ type: 'database' }` hook. A project-db write is delivered as the event\n676\t`project/db.<table>.<event>` (`event` ∈ `insert|update|remove`); the emitted payload IS\n677\tthe written row. Subscribe with an event hook and (usually) a project `db` emitter def:\n678\t\n679\t```typescript\n680\t// Producer: turn every insert into feed_items into a typed project event.\n681\tconst evt = [\n682\t  \"export default {\",\n683\t  \"  type: 'db',\",\n684\t  \"  on: { table: 'feed_items', event: 'insert' },\",\n685\t  \"  emits: { 'item.added': { payload: { id: 'string', title: 'string' } } },\",\n686\t  \"  emit: (row) => [{ event: 'item.added', payload: { id: row.row.id, title: row.row.title } }],\",\n687\t  \"};\",\n688\t].join(\"\\n\");\n689\twriteProjectEvent('feed-writes', evt);\n690\t// Consumer: react to project/item.added (or directly to project/db.feed_items.insert).\n691\t```\n692\t\n693\t## Scheduled polling — a `cron` EMITTER DEF (events/, with a `ctx.state` cursor)\n694\t\n695\tWhen the user wants to POLL a source on a schedule (\"every 30 minutes, check X for new items and\n696\tstore them\"), author a `cron` EMITTER DEF with `writeProjectEvent` (it goes in `events/`, NOT\n697\t`hooks/`). It has exactly one of `every` (`'<n>m|h|d'`) or `daily` (`'HH:MM'`), an async\n698\t`emit(ctx)` that polls via `ctx.callConnection`, and a persisted `ctx.state` KV it uses as a\n699\tcursor so a re-poll never re-emits an item it already saw. Pair it with a hook that stores each\n700\temitted item (the cron emit is PURE — it has NO `db`; it emits, a hook inserts):\n701\t\n702\t```typescript\n703\t// events/poll-demo-source.ts — poll the demo source every 30m; ctx.state.lastId is the cursor.\n704\tconst evt = [\n705\t  \"export default {\",\n706\t  \"  type: 'cron',\",\n707\t  \"  every: '30m',\",                                  // EXACTLY one of every / daily\n708\t  \"  connections: ['demo'],\",                         // the installed provider ctx.callConnection may reach\n709\t  \"  emits: { 'source.item': { payload: { id: 'string', text: 'string' } } },\",\n710\t  \"  async emit(ctx) {\",\n711\t  \"    const since = (ctx.state && ctx.state['lastId']) || '0';\",   // persisted cursor\n712\t  \"    let items = [];\",\n713\t  \"    try { const res = await ctx.callConnection('demo', { method: 'GET', path: '/items', query: { since } });\",\n714\t  \"          items = (res && res.data && res.data.items) || []; } catch { items = []; }\",\n715\t  \"    if (ctx.state && items.length) ctx.state['lastId'] = String(items[items.length - 1].id);\",  // advance cursor → next tick sees only newer\n716\t  \"    return items.map((it) => ({ event: 'source.item', payload: { id: String(it.id), text: String(it.text || '') } }));\",\n717\t  \"  },\",\n718\t  \"};\",\n719\t].join(\"\\n\");\n720\twriteProjectEvent('poll-demo-source', evt);\n721\t// Then a hook stores each polled item (do NOT re-declare an event the tips db emitter already owns):\n722\twriteProjectHook('store-polled-item', [\n723\t  \"export default { type: 'event', on: { event: 'project/source.item' },\",\n724\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => { const it = input; await db.insert('tips', { headline: String(it.text||'').slice(0,160), body: String(it.text||''), source: 'demo-poll', status: 'new', summary: '' }); } };\",\n725\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n726\t```\n727\t\n728\tThe `ctx.state` cursor is what makes a re-poll idempotent: because you advance `lastId` past every\n729\titem you emitted, the next tick's `since` skips them, so two consecutive runs never store the same\n730\titem twice. NEVER put a cron poll in a `handler` string that fabricates its own loop — use the def.\n731\t\n732\t## Cron hooks (scheduled AGENT run, not a poll)\n733\t\n734\tFor a scheduled AGENT action (not a source poll) a time-based HOOK uses `type: 'cron'`\n735\t(`every: '<n>m|h|d'` or `daily: 'HH:MM'`) and a `trigger` (or `handler`):\n736\t\n737\t```typescript\n738\tconst cron = [\n739\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '1d', trigger: 'system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app' };\",\n740\t].join(\"\\n\");\n741\twriteProjectHook('daily-refresh', cron);\n742\t```\n743\t\n744\tGuidelines:\n745\t\n746\t- **The SCHEDULE is declared, never re-implemented in the body.** The host decides when a cron\n747\t  hook is due (and, on boot, runs a window it missed while the pod was asleep — pods scale to\n748\t  zero). So express the cadence in the DEF and let the handler do its work **every time it is\n749\t  invoked**:\n750\t\n751\t  ```typescript\n752\t  // ✅ weekly — declared. Fires on schedule, catches up a missed window, and a manual\n753\t  //    \"run now\" (Studio / the hook-run endpoint) actually does the work.\n754\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '7d', trigger: 'kitchen/planner#weekly_plan' };\"\n755\t\n756\t  // ❌ NEVER: a daily cron that re-implements \"weekly\" by returning early on the wrong day.\n757\t  //    It skips every catch-up run, and a manual run silently does nothing.\n758\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', daily: '06:00', handler: async ({ db }) => {\",\n759\t  \"  if (new Date().getDay() !== 0) return;   // ← the bug: the handler must not gate on the clock\",\n760\t  ```\n761\t\n762\t  A handler may skip work that is genuinely already DONE (idempotence — \"this week's plan\n763\t  already exists, nothing to do\"), but it must never refuse to run because of the wall clock.\n764\t- Prefer a code `handler` over a `trigger` when the reaction is a simple filter/relay — no\n765\t  agent, no LLM cost. But when the rule needs genuine reasoning (summarize/classify/draft/\n766\t  decide), you MUST invoke a model — a `trigger` to an agent, or `ctx.delegate` from a\n767\t  handler (see \"When the rule needs a MODEL\"). Never fake it with hand-written string logic.\n768\t- Only list a provider in `connections:` that the user has installed; an unlisted provider\n769\t  throws at call time.\n770\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_XOUkCCKPWXZ8vWn7RxhEWgPz","session_id":"625ee3e5-57b1-42a3-9cc2-762259deb6f8","uuid":"20cd4fc4-2102-4543-a178-c8c219e64607","timestamp":"2026-07-16T03:56:25.436Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace automator build failure"}
