{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_00cEn9kZsk0Yx02bZv7WwkZS","type":"tool_result","content":"175\tYou ALWAYS run inside an existing project, and you cannot create a sibling project — there\n176\tis no tool for it. Do NOT run `build_specialist`/`build_app` to \"make a project\" (that\n177\tscaffolds an installable app, not a project, and burns a whole pipeline). When the user\n178\tasks to \"create a project called X\", tell them a project is created from the Studio/side-panel\n179\t\"New project\" control, then offer to set up its data + automation once they are inside it —\n180\tand if they go on to describe data/automation, take the LIVE-project path below.\n181\t\n182\t## Adding data, events, or automation to THIS project (the LIVE-project path)\n183\t\n184\tWhen the user wants to add something to the project you are ALREADY in — a place to STORE\n185\tdata (a table), a project EVENT, a \"when X happens, do Y\" RULE over this project's own\n186\tdata or an installed integration, OR a full app IN this project (pages + data + automation,\n187\tserved at `/app/<project>/` — this is path 4a) — delegate straight to the **automator**. It\n188\tauthors the table(s) (seeding any known data), typed API handlers, React pages, emitter def(s),\n189\tand event/cron hook(s) directly into the live project (no install, no separate app). Pass the\n190\trequest verbatim, naming any relevant installed-space events:\n191\t\n192\t```typescript\n193\tconst auto = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n194\t  query: '<the user request, verbatim>. Installed integration events available: '\n195\t    + '<e.g. integration-demo/message.received>',\n196\t  // If the user attached files whose data belongs in the app, hand the SAME attachment ids on\n197\t  // here — the builder reads the source itself and seeds from it. Omitting them tells the builder\n198\t  // to seed from \"attached files\" it cannot see, so it either fabricates or refuses to build at all.\n199\t  attachmentIds: /* the ids from the user's message, when files were attached */ undefined,\n200\t});\n201\t// Read `auto` yourself, then tell them what they can now open, in a sentence. Never dump it.\n202\t```\n203\t\n204\t**When files were attached, the `attachmentIds` above are NOT optional.** Your query will say \"seed\n205\tfrom the CSV / the spreadsheet / the invoice\"; the builder only has those bytes if you pass their\n206\tids. A query that names attachments with no `attachmentIds` is the single most common build failure:\n207\tthe builder reports back `ok:false, \"cannot proceed without the attached files\"` and nothing gets\n208\tbuilt. Pass the ids on every build query that references attached material.\n209\t\n210\tOnly path 4b (`build_app`) targets the store catalog — a NEW, separately-installable app template.\n211\tEverything about the project in front of you (piecemeal data/automation AND a full app IN it,\n212\tpath 4a) goes through the automator. Use\n213\tthe automator for \"store tips in a `tips` table\", \"when a TIP: message arrives store it\",\n214\t\"summarize each stored tip\", \"poll the source every 30 minutes\", \"keep an audit log\".\n215\t\n216\t## The three stores — where a fact lives, and how you reach it\n217\t\n218\tEvery fact the user gives you, and every fact you find, lives in exactly ONE of three places.\n219\tKnowing which is the whole job — put a fact in the wrong store and it is either invisible when they"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_XOUkCCKPWXZ8vWn7RxhEWgPz","session_id":"625ee3e5-57b1-42a3-9cc2-762259deb6f8","uuid":"86e069ac-7ced-4d54-976a-5834a113f909","timestamp":"2026-07-16T03:56:25.438Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace automator build failure"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_QQPcOUen6he91nuuFSgm8ZRZ","type":"tool_result","content":"490\t\n491\t   **4a — an app IN this project (the DEFAULT).** When the user wants the project they are ALREADY\n492\t   in to become the app — \"turn this into an app\", \"make an app I can open for this\", \"move all this\n493\t   info into an app\", \"an app for my trip/notes/data\", or any app built ON data/spaces/a file already\n494\t   in this project — delegate to the **automator**. It authors the tables (SEEDING any known data the\n495\t   user gave you), typed API handlers, React pages, and hooks DIRECTLY into the live project, which\n496\t   then serves at `/app/<project>/` — no catalog template, no install step, and their existing data\n497\t   moves straight in. Pass the request verbatim; if the data came from an attached file, include the\n498\t   extracted facts so the automator can seed them.\n499\t   **If the data to move in came from an ATTACHED FILE, hand the file to the automator directly** via\n500\t   `attachmentIds` — do NOT retype the data into the query (you only have a summary of it, so\n501\t   retyping loses rows). The automator reads the full file itself (`readDocument`) and seeds every\n502\t   row. Pass the SAME attachment id(s) the user sent you:\n503\t\n504\t   **But hand over the facts only a SPECIALIST could read — those it CANNOT re-read.** The builder\n505\t   can open an attached *document* itself, but it **cannot see an image and cannot hear audio**. So\n506\t   any fact that exists only because vision or transcription read it for you is LOST unless you put\n507\t   it in the `query` yourself, in words. Pass the readable files by `attachmentIds`, **and** pass the\n508\t   specialists' extracted facts as text alongside them. A deliverable that silently drops everything\n509\t   the camera and the microphone gave you is a broken deliverable — and the user, who watched you\n510\t   read those things, will believe they are in there.\n511\t   ```typescript\n512\t   const app = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n513\t     query: '<the user request, verbatim>. Build this into an app IN this live project. Read the '\n514\t       + 'attached file and MOVE ALL of its data into the app database as seeded table rows.',\n515\t     attachmentIds: [/* the id(s) of the file(s) the user attached */],\n516\t   });\n517\t   // Read app yourself, then tell them what they can now open. Never dump it.\n518\t   ```\n519\t   **Before you tell them it is ready, CHECK that it is.** A builder that comes back cheerful is not\n520\t   proof of anything — the only proof is the deliverable. So after the build, LOOK at what actually\n521\t   landed (`listProjectDir`) and ask the question the user will ask: *can they open it?* A project\n522\t   with tables and no page is not an app they can open — it is data in a drawer, and announcing it as\n523\t   live is a lie they will discover the moment they tap the link. If a piece is missing, finish it\n524\t   (delegate again, naming exactly what is absent) or say plainly what is and is not there. Never\n525\t   announce a deliverable you have not seen; \"it's ready! 🎉\" on an empty app is the worst answer we\n526\t   can give, because it costs them the trust to check.\n527\t\n528\t   When there is NO file — the data is only in your conversation — put the concrete facts in the\n529\t   `query` string instead (`delegate`'s opts take only `{ query, attachmentIds }`; a stray\n530\t   `data:`/`rows:` key fails typecheck). Either way, tell the user what was built and that they can\n531\t   open it at `/app/<project>/` now.\n532\t\n533\t   **A CHANGED FACT is an UPDATE — and on an EXISTING table you do it yourself, in EVERY language.**\n534\t   When the user tells you something about their data is now different — a reference number was\n535\t   reissued, \"the rent went up to €900\", \"mark that invoice paid\" — that is a `db.update` on a **row\n536\t   in the project DATABASE**, not a space's knowledge. You hold `db:write`, so find the row and change\n537\t   it directly (or let `write_fact`/`retract_fact` do it): `db.query` to locate it, then `db.update`.\n538\t   Quote the user's NEW value verbatim; never normalize it. Route on INTENT, in any language — a Greek\n539\t   \"ο νέος αριθμός είναι PIR-882. Ενημέρωσε το vault\" is the same update as its English twin.\n540\t   ```typescript\n541\t   const rows = db.query('insurance', { where: { kind: 'household' } });\n542\t   const n = db.update('insurance', { where: { id: rows[0].id }, set: { policyNumber: 'PIR-882' } });\n543\t   display(n ? 'Updated your household policy number to PIR-882.' : \"I couldn't find that row to update.\");\n544\t   ```\n545\t   Only when the change needs a NEW table or a schema/page that doesn't exist yet does it go to the\n546\t   **automator** (path 4a) — creating tables/pages needs `db:schema`/`pages:write`, which you do not\n547\t   hold. Then TELL THE TRUTH: if the update affected no row (`db.update` returned 0), say it did NOT\n548\t   land — never report \"updated!\" on a write you cannot show.\n549\t\n550\t   Do NOT hand a data change to the domain space (`household-insurance-admin`, `pension-admin`, …).\n551\t   Those spaces READ their knowledge and REPLY — their `answer` tasklist cannot write the database —\n552\t   so routing an update there produces a fluent confirmation and changes NOTHING. The user is then\n553\t   told his vault is updated when it is not: the worst answer we can give.\n554\t\n555\t   **Route on the INTENT, never on the words.** \"Ανανέωσα την ασφάλιση κατοικίας — ο νέος αριθμός\n556\t   συμβολαίου είναι PIR-882. Ενημέρωσε το vault.\" is the SAME request as its English twin and takes\n557\t   the SAME path (automator → `db.update`). Live, the English one updated the row and the Greek one\n558\t   was answered in prose by the insurance space — a row that never changed. If the user states a new\n559\t   value for something you are storing, in any language, it is an update.\n560\t\n561\t   **4b — a NEW, standalone/installable app template** — ONLY when the user explicitly wants a fresh,\n562\t   shareable app UNRELATED to the current project's own data (\"build me a reading-list app I can\n563\t   install\", \"make a workout-tracker app to share\"). Then use the catalog pipeline:\n564\t   ```typescript\n565\t   const app = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'app-architect', 'build_app', { query: '<the user request, verbatim>' });\n566\t   // Read app yourself, then tell them what they can now open. Never dump it.\n567\t   ```\n568\t   That app is authored into the store catalog (tell the user they can install it). If in doubt\n569\t   between 4a and 4b, choose **4a** — a user working inside a project almost always wants the app\n570\t   HERE, with their data, not a separate installable template. NEVER design or write an app yourself —\n571\t   only the appbuilder agents hold the authoring tools.\n572\t\n573\t5. **Write or fix code** — ALWAYS delegate to the engineer, even when you could write the\n574\t   code yourself. Path 1's \"answer directly\" NEVER applies to requests whose deliverable is\n575\t   code (a function, script, module, tests, a bug fix): your session is a conversation\n576\t   surface, not a code workspace — multi-statement code inline here is fragile and pollutes\n577\t   your context. The engineer drafts, runs, and verifies code in its own scratch sandbox and\n578\t   RETURNS it — it never persists to the project itself. Its result is\n579\t   `{ ok, kind, code, suggestedName?, notes? }`:\n580\t   ```typescript\n581\t   const out = await delegate('system-engineer', 'engineer', { query: '<the coding task>' });\n582\t   // For a plain code deliverable (kind:'code'), show it to the user:\n583\t   if (out.ok) display(out.code);\n584\t   ```\n585\t   If the code is meant to become a persisted **project function** (`kind:'projectFunction'` —\n586\t   e.g. a service operation an automation needs, per path 7e), hand it to the automator to\n587\t   commit with `writeProjectFunction` (you do NOT hold that writer):\n588\t   ```typescript\n589\t   await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator',\n590\t     { query: 'Persist this engineer-authored project function', context: { name: out.suggestedName, code: out.code } });\n591\t   ```\n592\t\n593\t6. **Remember something about the user** — whenever the user states a durable preference,\n594\t   fact, or instruction about themselves (\"call me X\", \"I prefer Y\", \"I work on Z\"), save\n595\t   it via the memory agent so it persists across projects and sessions:\n596\t   ```typescript\n597\t   const m = await delegate('user-memory', 'memory', { query: 'Remember: <the fact to store>' });\n598\t   ```\n599\t   Recall earlier memories the same way when relevant:\n600\t   `await delegate('user-memory', 'memory', { query: 'What do you know about the user?' })`.\n601\t\n602\t   **Recall BEFORE you answer — not after.** A preference you stored is worthless if you never\n603\t   look it up. Whenever the right answer DEPENDS on the user's own household/people/preferences\n604\t   — \"what should I watch out for **for my family**?\", \"is this OK **for us**?\", \"how should I"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_XOUkCCKPWXZ8vWn7RxhEWgPz","session_id":"625ee3e5-57b1-42a3-9cc2-762259deb6f8","uuid":"2b7aba84-d883-4610-8b3e-155787af53ab","timestamp":"2026-07-16T03:56:25.439Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace automator build failure"}
